definition.value: A synapse in which an action potential in the presynaptic cell increases the probability of an action potential occurring in the postsynaptic cell.
A synapse in which an action potential in the presynaptic cell reduces the probability of an action potential occurring in the postsynaptic cell.
The molecular function that accepts an input of one form and creates an output of a different form.

The binding activity of a molecule that brings together two or more molecules through a selective, non-covalent, often stoichiometric interaction, permitting those molecules to function in a coordinated way.
A nonmotile primary cilium that is found at the apical surface of auditory receptor cells. The kinocilium is surrounded by actin-based stereocilia.

label.value: collagen and cuticulin-based cuticle extracellular matrix

definition.value: A collagen and cuticulin-based noncellular, multilayered structure that is synthesized by an underlying ectodermal (hypodermal) cell layer. The cuticle serves essential functions in body morphology, locomotion, and environmental protection. An example of this component is found in Caenorhabditis elegans.

label.value: collagen and cuticulin-based cuticle extracellular matrix part

definition.value: Any constituent part of the collagen and cuticulin-based cuticle extracellular matrix, a collagen and cuticulin-based noncellular, multilayered structure that is synthesized by an underlying ectodermal (hypodermal) cell layer.

label.value: surface coat of collagen and cuticulin-based cuticle extracellular matrix

definition.value: An electron dense, amorphous envelope that comprises the outermost layer of the cuticle. The surface coat is loosely apposed to the epicuticle, has distinct biochemical properties, is synthesized by cells other than the underlying hypodermis, and is labile. In addition to serving as a lubricant to protect against abrasion and dehydration, the surface coat may also play important roles in infection and immune evasion. An example of this component is found in Caenorhabditis elegans.

label.value: epicuticle of collagen and cuticulin-based cuticle extracellular matrix

definition.value: A lipid-containing layer of cuticle that lies between the cortical layer and the surface coat. An example of this component is found in Caenorhabditis elegans.

label.value: cortical layer of collagen and cuticulin-based cuticle extracellular matrix

definition.value: The cuticle layer that lies directly beneath the lipid-containing epicuticle. The cortical layer contains collagens and insoluble, non-collagenous cuticulins and is characterized by a distinct annular pattern consisting of regularly spaced annular ridges delineated by annular furrows. An example of this component is found in Caenorhabditis elegans.

The extracellular matrix that is a regularly spaced circumferential ridge present in the cortical region of the cuticle. Annuli are delineated by annular furrows and are present throughout the cuticle with the exception of lateral regions where longitudinal alae are present.

The extracellular matrix part that is a regularly spaced indentation in the outer cortical layer of the cuticle. The pattern of annular furrows corresponds to sites of invaginations in hypodermal cell membranes that, in turn, correspond to submembranous regions where actin microfilament bundles assemble early in lethargus, the first phase of the molting cycle in which activity and feeding decline.

label.value: medial layer of collagen and cuticulin-based cuticle extracellular matrix

definition.value: The fluid-filled cuticle layer that lies between the cortical and basal layers and is characterized by the presence of regularly spaced columnar struts that lie on either side of the annular furrows and link the two surrounding layers. In C. elegans, a defined medial layer is found only in adult animals.

label.value: basal layer of collagen and cuticulin-based cuticle extracellular matrix

definition.value: The layer of cuticle most closely apposed to the hypodermal cells. The morphology of the basal layer varies with life stage. In adult C. elegans animals, the basal layers is comprised of three sublayers -  two fibrous layers whose fibers run in clockwise and counter-clockwise directions meeting one another at a 60 degree angle, and an amorphous basal layer that lies underneath the fibrous layers and directly contacts the hypodermis. In C. elegans dauer and L1 larval stage animals, the basal layer is characterized by a striated pattern that appears to derive from interwoven laminae. An example of this component is found in Caenorhabditis elegans.

label.value: alae of collagen and cuticulin-based cuticle extracellular matrix

definition.value: Raised, thickened cuticular ridges that run longitudinally, and in parallel, along the left and right sides of the animal. The alae lie above the hypodermal cells known as the lateral seam cells. In C. elegans, alae are produced in L1 larvae, dauer larvae and adult stage animals, where they consist of three, five, and three ridges of distinct morphology, respectively.

label.value: viral gene silencing in virus induced gene silencing

definition.value: The posttranscriptional gene silencing of viral genes after viral infection.

label.value: host gene silencing in virus induced gene silencing

definition.value: The posttranscriptional gene silencing of host genes that are homologous to viral genes after viral infection.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the inactivation of gene expression by a posttranscriptional mechanism.

label.value: positive regulation of posttranscriptional gene silencing

definition.value: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of the inactivation of gene expression by a posttranscriptional mechanism.

label.value: negative regulation of posttranscriptional gene silencing

definition.value: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of the inactivation of gene expression by a posttranscriptional mechanism.

label.value: viral triggering of virus induced gene silencing

definition.value: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of the inactivation of gene expression of both viral genes and host homologues to those genes by a posttranscriptional mechanism in a virally infected cell.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a cilium.
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a stereocilium.
Combining with a brain-derived neurotrophic factor and transmitting the signal across the plasma membrane to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with the peptide apelin to initiate a change in cell activity.
Either of two different areas at opposite ends of an axis of a cell.

Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the synthesis of antisense RNA, an RNA molecule complementary in sequence to another RNA or DNA molecule, which, by binding the latter, acts to inhibit its function and|or completion of synthesis, on a template of DNA.

label.value: negative regulation of antisense RNA transcription

definition.value: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of the synthesis of antisense RNA, an RNA molecule complementary in sequence to another RNA or DNA molecule, which, by binding the latter, acts to inhibit its function and|or completion of synthesis, on a template of DNA.

label.value: positive regulation of antisense RNA transcription

definition.value: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of the synthesis of antisense RNA, an RNA molecule complementary in sequence to another RNA or DNA molecule, which, by binding the latter, acts to inhibit its function and|or completion of synthesis, on a template of DNA.
A clathrin-sculpted lipid bilayer membrane-enclosed vesicle after clathrin release.
A clathrin-sculpted lipid bilayer membrane-enclosed vesicle after clathrin release and containing glutamate.
A clathrin-sculpted lipid bilayer membrane-enclosed vesicle after clathrin release and containing acetylcholine.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted acetylcholine transport vesicle.
The volume enclosed by the membrane of the clathrin-sculpted acetylcholine transport vesicle.
The lipid bilayer surrounding a clathrin-sculpted glutamate transport vesicle.
The volume enclosed by the membrane of the clathrin-sculpted glutamate transport vesicle.
The volume enclosed by the membrane of a cytoplasmic membrane-bounded vesicle.

label.value: regulation of nuclear-transcribed mRNA poly(A) tail shortening

definition.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of poly(A) tail shortening of a nuclear-transcribed mRNA. Poly(A) tail shortening is the decrease in length of the poly(A) tail of an mRNA from full length to an oligo(A) length.

label.value: negative regulation of nuclear-transcribed mRNA poly(A) tail shortening

definition.value: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of poly(A) tail shortening of a nuclear-transcribed mRNA. Poly(A) tail shortening is the decrease in length of the poly(A) tail of an mRNA from full length to an oligo(A) length.

label.value: positive regulation of nuclear-transcribed mRNA poly(A) tail shortening

definition.value: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of poly(A) tail shortening of a nuclear-transcribed mRNA. Poly(A) tail shortening is the decrease in length of the poly(A) tail of an mRNA from full length to an oligo(A) length.
Increases the activity of phosphatidylcholine-sterol O-acyltransferase, an enzyme that converts cholesterol and phosphatidylcholine (lecithins) to cholesteryl esters and lyso-phosphatidylcholines.
Increases the activity of a lipase, an enzyme that catalyzes of the hydrolysis of a lipid.
Increases the activity of a lipoprotein lipase, an enzyme that catalyzes of the hydrolysis of a lipid within a lipoprotein.
Stops, prevents or reduces the activity of a lysozyme, an enzyme that hydrolyses the beta- (1,4) glycosidic bond between N-acetylmuramic acid and N-acetylglucosamine in peptidoglycan.

label.value: regulation of transcription initiation from RNA polymerase II promoter

definition.value: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of a process involved in starting transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter.

label.value: positive regulation of transcription initiation from RNA polymerase II promoter

definition.value: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of a process involved in starting transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter.
Differentiated cytoplasm associated with a pole of an oocyte, egg or early embryo that will be inherited by the cells that will give rise to the germ line.

Modulates the activity of GTP cyclohydrolase I. GTP cyclohydrolase I activity catalyzes the reaction -  GTP + 2 H2O -eq- formate + 2-amino-4-hydroxy-6-(erythro-1,2,3-trihydroxypropyl)-dihydropteridine triphosphate.

The membrane surrounding the outer segment of a vertebrate photoreceptor. The photoreceptor inner segment contains mitochondria, ribosomes and membranes where opsin molecules are assembled and passed to be part of the outer segment discs.
A structure that lies outside the plasma membrane and surrounds the egg. The fertilization envelope forms from the vitelline membrane after fertilization as a result of cortical granule release.
